  "text": "The serum levels of CK and LDH were also measured as indirect biomarkers of muscle damage. In this regard, Clarkson and Hubal [CITATION_1] stated that CK levels are expected to rise over 100% following resistance exercise in comparison to their baseline levels and that it remains elevated for several days following resistance exercise. However, no significant increases from baseline values in the levels of CK and LDH were observed over time for any of the conditions tested. Although LDH levels significantly increased for all conditions 48 h post-exercise in comparison to 24 h post-exercise, this difference is likely due to normal daily variations in serum levels of LDH rather than the exercise performed, as no significant dif- 14. Loenneke JP, Fahs CA, Rossow LM, Sherk VD, Thiebaud",
